<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-04-01T14:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-04-01T14:30:00-05:00" n="3" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d3">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">710.G/90: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Uruguay (<persName type="from">Wright</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Montevideo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-01T16:00:00-03:30">April 1,
                                    1932—4 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received 5:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>20. I infer that Uruguay’s attitude at meeting of the Board of Pan
                            American Union April 5th will be that of no opposition to postponement
                            of Conference for a definite period of from 6 months to 2 years if
                            proposed by Brazil or any other country, but of objection to indefinite
                            postponement as jeopardizing spirit of Pan-Americanism and objects of
                            conferences.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Wright</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>